title: For Sale:  Wolf 7.62x39 non corrosive FMJ & Wolf .223
postcontent:
Wolf FMJ non corrosive, polymer coated, 1,000 rounds for $229.50, shipping is about $22 bucks, don't fall prety to the people here trying to sell the ammo for more than it's worth:


http://sgammo.com/product/wolf-performance-ammunition/1000-round-case-762x39-full-metal-jacket-123-grain-wolf-performa


Don't fall prey to the rumors that the ammo will disapear (or price skyrocketing) due to the Russian ban (if it happens):


http://www.thebangswitch.com/is-the-x39-world-coming-to-an-end/


The people here selling ammo are doing only harm to the gun community by overpricing their products and spreading fear to try to make a buck out at your expense, shop smart, use websites like www.slickguns.com and www.gunbot.net to find good deal on ammo, never buy 7.62x39 ammo for over 24 cents a round, that's $4.80 a box of 20, the deals are always around, never buy corrosive ammo, it's not worth it. Btw that same website sells .233 ammo dirt cheap, you can get 1k rounds of 7.92x39 and 500 rounds of .223 FMJ wolf ammo shipped to your doorstep for $400, thats 7.62x39  for 24 cents at round and .223 for 31 cents a round delivered to your doorstep, shipping included! No need to drive and meet someone, no need to get cash from the bank, think of the time wasted meeting people here to buy ammo, think of the gas expense, unless the person lives 5 minutes from your house(thats 10 min round trip), sells the ammo for the same price online or cheaper and there is a bank on the way, you are better off buying it online and getting it delivered to you.


Another thing to think about, if the person lives 30 miles from your house (you can use google maps to find out), and you get lets say 20 miles per gallon on your car, round trip thats 60 miles, so you just used 3 gallons of gas to meet that person, if the gas is about 3.33 per gallon you just spent $10 just to meet that person! That's not taking into account any toll money, you can check how many miles per gallon your car does at http://www.fueleconomy.gov, but know that the list is your car brand new in perfect conditions, not how it is nowdays, but at least you get a ballpark.



Good luck and shop smart!

postcontent:
This is my Palmetto Stae Armory 16" carbine that I built for coyote/hogs. It has an Armasight Orion 4x Generation 1+ night vision scope with attached IR illuminator. I have also added a second IR illuminator on the left side near the bipod.  All that comes with the rifle. The NV will be in it's orignal box, the carbine will be in a Palmetto State Army box. The bipod and second IR are mounted on a Magpul MOE handguard (mid length) the Carbine also has Magpul MOE trigger guard and the Magpul MOE stock.

The combination works excellently out to 100 yards plus in all conditions and further depending on ambient light. It is easy to zero in daylight using the pinhole in the lens cover but I actually used a laser bore sight at night to dial it in. NV includes the batteries. Here's a link to YouTube so you can see the Armasight Orion.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_embedded&v=phOAy1W7k5A

Once upon a time, a "dissipator" AR was created by taking a 20" rifle-length gas system upper and cutting the barrel down to 16".  This allowed the shooter to keep the long sight radius of a rifle for accuracy, but keep the carbine length barrel for maneuverability.  The proximity of the gas port to the muzzle, however, played havoc with timing and made reliability a hit or miss proposition.   Advances in AR technology  have produced reliable carbine and mid-length gas systems, that can be hidden using low-profile gas blocks.  This allows for a front sight base to be pinned in the rifle position for the longer sight radius without the worry of the unorthodox gas port location affecting operation.   We use the term "mock" to differentiate our dissipator from a cut-down rifle length version. 

Our Hammer-Forged Mid-length dissipator uses a "Machine Gun Steel" barrel that is thick chrome-lined for durability and high pressure tested and magnetic particle inspected.

Barrel:  A proprietary blend of Hammer forged chrome molly vanadium made by FN that is referred to as "Machine Gun Steel" by virtue of its use in FN's M249 and M240 weapons.   The hammer forging process work hardens the steel, making it more durable.  In addition, the chrome process for the bore allows for a lining almost twice as thick as a standard M16 for enhanced durability.  Chambered in 5.56 NATO, with a 1/7 twist, M4 barrel extension, and a Mid-length gas system.   A2 style profile barrel is Mil-spec phosphate coated, High Pressure tested and Magnetic Particle inspected.  Barrel is finished off with a pinned F-marked front sight post in the Rifle position with sling swivel,  rifle length MOE handguards, and an A2 flash hider.

Upper: Forged 7075-T6 A3 AR upper is made to MIL-SPECS and hard coat anodized black for durability. Featuring machined T marks, and a mil-spec finish. These uppers are made for us right here in the USA by a mil-spec manufacturer.
